#Text=Rare Middle East cyclone batters Oman
#Text=Thursday , June 7 , 2007

#Text=Tropical Storm Gonu headed toward Iran today , after lashing Oman for two days with high winds and torrential rains , and causing at least 23 deaths and the evacuation of more than 20,000 people to emergency shelters .
#Text=Concern was high for the oil industry , as rough seas kept tankers from leaving their ports .
#Text=Such storms are rare in the Middle East .
#Text=Early today , Gonu was weakening and was downgraded to a tropical storm .
#Text=The Joint Typhoon Warning Center projected the storm to continue weakening as it made landfall on Iran 's southeastern coast .
#Text=Offshore Iranian oil installations were expected to be spared , officials said .
#Text=Oman lashed
#Text=In
#Text=the Omani capital , Muscat
#Text=yesterday , there were torrential rains and howling winds , a rarity in the quiet coastal city .
#Text=Streets were flooded and emergency vehicles were useless .
#Text=Flights were canceled at Oman 's Seeb International Airport .
#Text=Twenty-three deaths were reported by Omani authorities today .
#Text=Electricity and phone lines were out and roads flooded .
#Text=Police said a body washed ashore in Sur .
#Text=There were also reports of people trapped in homes in low-lying areas of the capital .
#Text=Authorities used mobile-phone text messages to warn people away from dangerous areas .
#Text=Residents were warned to stay at home , or seek shelter in buildings that could withstand the harsh weather .
#Text=Shareefa bint Khalfan , Omani minister of social development , said more than 20,000 people were evacuated to government shelters .
#Text=At Oman 's weather center , where records have been kept since 1890 , metorologists said Gonu was likely the strongest storm to hit Oman since 1977 .
#Text=Milder tropical storms are common mid-May to late June .
#Text=Iran prepares
#Text=In Iran , hundreds of residents of Chabahr , a port on the Gulf of Oman , were evacuated .
